Derek, you said before that currently not all fingerprint 
classification is done by machine.  Is there a particular step in 
the process that the roving eye can fill?  For example, is the 
experiment you are doing now a task usually done by human eye?
It seems even if the entire process of fingerprint identification 
can't be done with the roving eye, it may still be able to fill some 
crucial link in the chain.

ken

--- In neat@yahoogroups.com, Derek James <djames@g...> wrote:
> On Wed, 17 Nov 2004 22:20:55 -0000, Kenneth Stanley
> <kstanley@c...> wrote:
> > 
> > 
> > Man, I just gotta say, this is a really cool demo.  I think 
what's
> > so compelling about it is that you are watching the 
eye "thinking."
> > Hopefully if you get a paper accepted you'll get a chance to show
> > this demo.  I think it would get a really good reaction.
> 
> Thanks...we hope so too.  Right now we're wrangling with the NIST
> Special Database 4, a database of preclassified fingerprint images
> that's a standard benchmark in a lot of the literature.  It's from
> 1992, and the images are compressed and stored in a proprietary
> format, and the software is clunky and difficult to compile,
> and...welcome to the world of research. :)
> 
> We hope that we can get some good work done over the next month, 
and
> evolve the networks for a system that's able to generalize and 
perform
> well on a large test set.
> 
> We'll keep you guys posted on our progress.
> 
> Derek
